{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01Hd53eDzH5yZ4eUStpncZ2b","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-27\n     2→\n     3→**Sprint:** Epic 14 completion session\n     4→**Duration:** ~20 minutes\n     5→**Stories completed:** 14-4, 14-5, 14-6 (all verified and marked done)\n     6→**Epic status:** Epic 14 — DONE (all 7 stories complete)\n     7→\n     8→---\n     9→\n    10→## 1. Session Summary\n    11→\n    12→Three stories were verified and marked done in this session, completing Epic 14:\n    13→\n    14→- **14-5** (stack-aware-verify-dockerfile) — Tier A quick validation. Proof already existed with 10/10 PASS. Two precondition issues found and fixed before `codeharness verify` passed: stale AGENTS.md missing stats.ts entry, and stats.ts at 1.14% coverage (18 tests written to fix).\n    15→- **14-6** (subagent-status-ownership-time-budget) — Tier A quick validation. Proof already existed with 10/10 PASS. `codeharness verify` passed immediately.\n    16→- **14-4** (observability-backend-choice) — Unit-testable verification via subagent. ALL_PASS (10/10 ACs). 20 tool calls in the subagent, with one wasted Write (wrong proof format) and an overly broad grep.\n    17→\n    18→## 2. Issues Analysis\n    19→\n    20→### Category: State management\n    21→- **`state set` does not trigger YAML regeneration.** The `state set` command writes to `sprint-state.json` but does not regenerate the derived `sprint-status.yaml`. Only `writeStateAtomic` (called by certain internal paths) does the regen. This caused multiple fix attempts and confusion about whether state was actually persisted.\n    22→\n    23→### Category: Stale documentation\n    24→- **AGENTS.md for `src/commands/` was missing `stats.ts` entry.** The `stats` command was added in a prior session but the AGENTS.md doc was not updated. This caused a verification precondition failure.\n    25→\n    26→### Category: Test coverage gap\n    27→- **`stats.ts` had 1.14% coverage.** The command was shipped without tests in a prior session. Had to write 18 tests to bring it to acceptable levels before verification could pass.\n    28→\n    29→### Category: Workflow gap\n    30→- **Proof documents existed for 14-5 and 14-6 but stories were stuck at \"verifying\".** The proofs were generated but nobody ran `codeharness verify` to validate them and transition the story state. Stories sat idle until this session picked them up.\n    31→\n    32→## 3. Cost Analysis\n    33→\n    34→**Cumulative project costs** (all epics, all time):\n    35→\n    36→| Metric | Value |\n    37→|--------|-------|\n    38→| Total API-equivalent cost | $556.06 |\n    39→| Total API calls | 4,098 |\n    40→| Average cost per story | $3.25 (140 stories) |\n    41→\n    42→**Token breakdown:**\n    43→- Cache reads: $347.42 (62%) — dominant cost, expected for long-context sessions\n    44→- Cache writes: $123.43 (22%)\n    45→- Output: $85.04 (15%)\n    46→- Input: $0.16 (0%)\n    47→\n    48→**Phase breakdown:**\n    49→- Verification: $318.51 (57.3%) — most expensive phase by far\n    50→- Orchestrator: $98.81 (17.8%)\n    51→- Retro: $56.27 (10.1%)\n    52→\n    53→**This session's stories in the top 10:**\n    54→- 14-4: $18.11 (148 calls) — most expensive of the three, due to subagent verification\n    55→- 14-5: $16.47 (122 calls) — inflated by coverage fix (18 new tests)\n    56→- 14-6: not in top 10 — cheap, immediate pass\n    57→\n    58→## 4. What Went Well\n    59→\n    60→- **3 stories verified in ~20 minutes** — efficient session with clear scope.\n    61→- **2 of 3 were quick proof validations** — proofs already existed, just needed the formal verify pass.\n    62→- **Coverage gap found and fixed** — stats.ts went from 1.14% to acceptable coverage with 18 new tests. The enforcement system caught a real gap.\n    63→- **Epic 14 completed** — all 7 stories done, clean closure.\n    64→\n    65→## 5. What Went Wrong\n    66→\n    67→- **`sprint-status.yaml` sync issues required multiple fix attempts.** After `state set`, the YAML was stale. Trying to fix it by re-running `state set` did not help because `state set` never triggers YAML regen. Had to find workarounds.\n    68→- **`state set` is unreliable for status transitions.** It writes JSON but skips derived artifacts. This is a recurring pain point across multiple sessions.\n    69→- **Prior session shipped stats.ts without tests.** The 1.14% coverage should have been caught at commit time, not during verification of an unrelated story.\n    70→\n    71→## 6. Lessons Learned\n    72→\n    73→1. **Always update `sprint-state.json` directly for status changes, not via `state set`.** The `state set` command is broken for this purpose — it does not regenerate derived files. Use the `node -e` approach to modify JSON atomically and then explicitly regenerate YAML if needed.\n    74→2. **Proof documents without a `codeharness verify` run are incomplete.** A proof file on disk does not mean the story is verified. The verify command must run to validate the proof and transition state. Tier A stories with passing proofs should be auto-verified.\n    75→3. **New commands need tests before merge.** The stats.ts gap should have been blocked by the harness enforcement, but it slipped through. Coverage checks need to run on the specific files changed, not just overall coverage.\n    76→\n    77→## 7. Action Items\n    78→\n    79→### Fix now\n    80→- [ ] **`state set` should trigger YAML regeneration** — or document the workaround prominently. Currently the only reliable path is to modify `sprint-state.json` directly with `node -e` and then call the YAML generation function. This trips up every session.\n    81→\n    82→### Fix soon\n    83→- [ ] **Auto-verify stories that have passing proofs.** Tier A stories (unit-testable, proof already on disk with ALL_PASS) should be automatically verified by Ralph during its sweep. No human or explicit `codeharness verify` call should be needed.\n    84→\n    85→### Backlog\n    86→- [ ] **Add verification-tier tags to all existing stories retroactively.** Epic 16 introduces the tier system, but existing completed stories have no tier metadata. Consider backfilling for historical analysis and to validate the tier classification logic.\n    87→\n    88→---\n    89→\n    90→# Session Retrospective — 2026-03-27 (Session 2)\n    91→\n    92→**Sprint:** Epic 14 close-out + Epic 16 kickoff\n    93→**Duration:** ~24 minutes\n    94→**Stories completed:** 14-4, 14-5, 14-6 (verified existing proofs), 16-1 (full lifecycle: dev, review, verify)\n    95→**Epic status:** Epic 14 — DONE (all 7 stories). Epic 16 — 1/8 done.\n    96→\n    97→---\n    98→\n    99→## 1. Session Summary\n   100→"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_0153HS6dcFJhZeHiRfL6Sjmx","session_id":"162680c7-17ac-40eb-b87b-353162776441","uuid":"bdb012e6-8661-4989-b635-ca6ac6d1ce5f","timestamp":"2026-03-27T14:21:41.450Z"}
